    <div class="petra"><h1>Petra</h1></div>
    <div class="about"><p>Petra is an ancient city in southern Jordan, renowned for its rock-cut architecture and water management system. Founded around the 6th century BC by the Nabataeans, a nomadic Arab tribe, Petra became a thriving trading hub due to its strategic location along major caravan routes connecting the Arabian Peninsula, Egypt, and the Levant.

        The city is best known for its dramatic structures carved directly into the rose-red sandstone cliffs, giving it the nickname "The Rose City." The most famous of these is the **Al-Khazneh** (The Treasury), a grand fa√ßade carved into a cliff face, which was originally a tomb. Other notable structures include the **Monastery** (Ad Deir), the **Royal Tombs**, and the **Theatre**.
        
        Petra's advanced water management system, including cisterns, channels, and dams, allowed the city to thrive in a desert environment, supporting a large population. The city fell into decline after the Roman conquest in the 2nd century AD and was largely forgotten by the Western world until it was rediscovered by Swiss explorer Johann Ludwig Burckhardt in 1812.
        
        In 1985, Petra was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site and was later named one of the **New Seven Wonders of the World** in 2007. Its breathtaking beauty and historical significance continue to make it one of the most iconic archaeological sites in the world.</p></div>
